---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Navbar from '../../components/Navbar.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/?$/, '/');
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Weighted Spatial Redistribution Algorithm"
  description="Implementation of Jonny Huck's weighted redistribution algorithm to resolve spatial ambiguity in geocoded Twitter data across Greater Manchester."
>
  <Navbar slot="nav" />

  <article>
    <header class="project-banner">
      <div class="banner-bg" style={`background-image: url('${base}images/assignment2/redistribution_grid.png')`}></div>
      <div class="banner-overlay"></div>
      <div class="container banner-content">
        <a href={`${base}projects`} class="back-link">← All Projects</a>
        <div class="banner-meta">
          <span class="grade-badge">82 / 100</span>
          <span class="tag">GIS Programming</span>
          <span class="tag">2025</span>
        </div>
        <h1>Weighted Spatial Redistribution</h1>
        <p class="banner-sub">Resolving Spatial Ambiguity with Population-Weighted GIS</p>
        <div class="banner-tags">
          {["Python", "GeoPandas", "Rasterio", "NumPy", "skimage"].map(t => (
            <span class="tag">{t}</span>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="container project-body">
      <div class="project-layout">
        <div class="prose">

          <h2>Project Overview</h2>
          <p>
            This project implements and extends Jonny Huck's (2015) spatial weighted redistribution
            algorithm to resolve the <strong>false hotspot problem</strong> in spatially ambiguous data.
            Passively geocoded tweets are collapsed to a single centroid of the local administrative
            boundary, creating misleading hotspots. This project reimplements the algorithm to diffuse
            those points across each admin area, informed by a population density weighting surface.
          </p>
          <p>
            The specific application: redistributing geocoded Twitter data about the Royal Wedding across
            Greater Manchester to visualise likely tweet origins and evaluate implications for advertising
            targeting strategies. This project achieved a grade of <strong>82</strong>.
          </p>

          <h2>Motivation</h2>
          <p>
            Passive geocoding collapses all tweets from an area to a single centroid — an extreme form
            of spatial generalisation that creates artefactual hotspots where real population may not
            peak. This distortion is particularly problematic in marketing, urban planning, and emergency
            services, where spatial precision drives resource allocation decisions.
          </p>
          <p>
            I explored how to translate methodological ambiguity into a computational workflow, achieving
            efficient raster-based processing while maintaining visual and statistical validity.
          </p>

          <h2>Key Design Decisions</h2>

          <h3>Spatial Indexing</h3>
          <p>
            Leveraged GeoPandas' <code>sindex</code> with R-trees to filter candidate points in
            logarithmic time, using <code>within()</code> checks to confirm geometry containment.
          </p>

          <h3>Efficient Geometry Filtering</h3>
          <p>
            Random seeds were batch-generated within bounding boxes and validated in vectorised NumPy
            operations, avoiding redundant loops and minimising memory overhead.
          </p>

          <h3>Raster Updates via Disk Buffers</h3>
          <p>
            Used <code>skimage.draw.disk()</code> to localise Euclidean decay calculations, avoiding
            computationally expensive full-raster iteration on every seed placement.
          </p>

          <figure>
            <img src={`${base}images/assignment2/False_Hotspots.png`} alt="False hotspots from spatially ambiguous point data" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>Figure 1: Collapsed tweet data creating artefactual hotspots due to spatial generalisation.</figcaption>
          </figure>

          <figure>
            <img src={`${base}images/assignment2/Redistribution.png`} alt="Redistributed tweet data using s=0.3 and W=25" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>Figure 2: Redistributed tweet data using s = 0.3 and W = 25, diffused across population density surface.</figcaption>
          </figure>

          <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
          <p>
            The 12-panel figure was created dynamically to visualise how the algorithm responds to
            changes in the <code>s</code> parameter (spatial ambiguity) and <code>W</code>
            (number of seed samples):
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Lower <code>s</code> values produce tight clusters — suitable for fine-resolution targeting (e.g., billboards)</li>
            <li>Higher <code>s</code> values broaden distributions — ideal for coarse targeting like regional radio</li>
            <li>Larger <code>W</code> values favour high-density areas; low <code>W</code> introduces greater stochastic spread</li>
          </ul>

          <figure>
            <img src={`${base}images/assignment2/redistribution_grid.png`} alt="12-panel sensitivity analysis grid" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>Figure 3: 12-panel dynamic sensitivity analysis showing effects of varying s and W on spatial redistribution.</figcaption>
          </figure>

          <h2>Challenges Overcome</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>MAUP and Scale Discrepancy:</strong> The tweet data's Level 3 admin areas didn't perfectly align with the redistribution shapefile, revealing critical spatial assumptions buried in generalisation pipelines.</li>
            <li><strong>Visualising Uncertainty:</strong> Rather than claim precision, the algorithm visualises likelihood — outputs are better suited to qualitative inference than point prediction.</li>
            <li><strong>Runtime Efficiency:</strong> Code executes in under 10 seconds, enabling multiple model runs for the 12-panel comparative output without memory bloat.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Reflections</h2>
          <p>
            This project demonstrates a solid understanding of spatial data uncertainty, Python-based
            geospatial workflows, and efficient algorithm design. Investing time in optimising for
            usability, flexibility, and clarity produced skills that translate directly into real-world
            GIS roles where data quality and uncertainty communication are critical.
          </p>
        </div>

        <aside class="project-sidebar">
          <div class="sidebar-card">
            <h3>Resources</h3>
            <div class="sidebar-links">
              <a href="/projects/assignment2/assignment2-writeup.pdf" target="_blank" class="sidebar-link">
                <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                  <path d="M14 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V8z"/>
                  <polyline points="14 2 14 8 20 8"/>
                </svg>
                Full Write-up (PDF)
              </a>
              <a href="https://github.com/MaxLarner/gis-portfolio-max-larner/blob/main/projects/assignment2/assignment2.py" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="sidebar-link">
                <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor">
                  <path d="M12 2C6.477 2 2 6.477 2 12c0 4.418 2.865 8.166 6.839 9.489.5.092.682-.217.682-.482 0-.237-.009-.868-.013-1.703-2.782.604-3.369-1.342-3.369-1.342-.454-1.154-1.11-1.462-1.11-1.462-.908-.62.069-.608.069-.608 1.003.07 1.531 1.03 1.531 1.03.892 1.529 2.341 1.087 2.91.832.092-.647.35-1.088.636-1.338-2.22-.253-4.555-1.11-4.555-4.943 0-1.091.39-1.984 1.029-2.683-.103-.253-.446-1.27.098-2.647 0 0 .84-.269 2.75 1.025A9.578 9.578 0 0 1 12 6.836a9.59 9.59 0 0 1 2.504.337c1.909-1.294 2.747-1.025 2.747-1.025.546 1.377.202 2.394.1 2.647.64.699 1.028 1.592 1.028 2.683 0 3.842-2.339 4.687-4.566 4.935.359.309.678.919.678 1.852 0 1.336-.012 2.415-.012 2.743 0 .267.18.578.688.48C19.138 20.163 22 16.418 22 12c0-5.523-4.477-10-10-10z"/>
                </svg>
                Python Source on GitHub
              </a>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sidebar-card">
            <h3>Skills Demonstrated</h3>
            <ul class="sidebar-skills">
              <li>Spatial data uncertainty modelling</li>
              <li>Raster processing & disk buffers</li>
              <li>Vectorised NumPy operations</li>
              <li>Algorithm efficiency & profiling</li>
              <li>Dynamic multi-panel visualisation</li>
              <li>MAUP and scale analysis</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <Footer slot="footer" />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .project-banner {
    position: relative;
    min-height: 420px;
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-end;
    padding-top: var(--nav-h);
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .banner-bg {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background-size: cover;
    background-position: center;
    filter: saturate(0.4) brightness(0.35);
  }
  .banner-overlay {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: linear-gradient(to top, rgba(8,13,24,1) 0%, rgba(8,13,24,0.5) 60%, rgba(8,13,24,0.2) 100%);
  }
  .banner-content {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
    padding-bottom: 3rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
  }
  .back-link {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.4rem;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--text-3);
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
    transition: color 0.15s ease;
  }
  .back-link:hover { color: var(--accent); }
  .banner-meta { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .banner-content h1 { font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 4vw, 3rem); margin-bottom: 0.4rem; }
  .banner-sub { font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--text-2); margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .banner-tags { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.4rem; }
  .project-body { padding-top: 3.5rem; padding-bottom: 2rem; }
  .project-layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 300px; gap: 4rem; align-items: start; }
  .project-sidebar { position: sticky; top: calc(var(--nav-h) + 2rem); }
  .sidebar-card {
    background: var(--bg-1);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .sidebar-card h3 {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--text-3);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.75rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .sidebar-links { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.6rem; }
  .sidebar-link {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.6rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--text-2);
    transition: color 0.15s ease;
  }
  .sidebar-link:hover { color: var(--accent); }
  .sidebar-skills { list-style: none; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem; padding: 0; }
  .sidebar-skills li {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--text-2);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    position: relative;
  }
  .sidebar-skills li::before { content: "→"; position: absolute; left: 0; color: var(--accent); font-size: 0.75rem; }
  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .project-layout { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 2.5rem; }
    .project-sidebar { position: static; }
  }
</style>
